J/AJ/.../...      Astrometric observations of Phobos        (Lai+, 2026)
================================================================================
Automated Shape-Model-Based Astrometry of Phobos from
    Mars Express SRC Images
    Wang-Xing Lai, Qing-Feng Zhang, Rui Zhang
================================================================================
Keywords: Astrometry --- Ephemerides --- Martian satellites --- Astrodynamics
          --- Astronomy image processing

Abstract:
    Mars Express (MEX) performed a series of Phobos flybys at distances ranging
	from 50 to 5500 km, spanning an observational baseline from January 2007 to
	December 2025. A total of 732 images were acquired by the Super Resolution
	Channel (SRC), from which spacecraft-centered right ascension and 
	declination of the Martian moon were determined across diverse orbital 
	phases and illumination conditions.

	Camera pointing were calibrated through background star observations 
	cross-matched against the Gaia DR3 catalog. Positional measurements were 
	obtained using FeatureMapping, a surface-feature-based astrometric technique 
	that determines the center-of-figure location of Phobos by matching 
	identified surface features against a reference control-point network and 
	3D shape model.

	Observed positions are compared against predicted ephemeris positions 
    computed from JPL MAR099, the current best-fit solution for the Martian 
    satellite system, which incorporates over a century of astrometric data 
    from ground-based, spacecraft, and rover observations. Residuals between 
    SRC-derived astrometry and MAR099 predictions are analyzed as a function 
    of time, flyby geometry, and image quality to assess systematic trends 
    and long-term ephemeris consistency.

	In conclusion, the extended 2007--2025 baseline---the longest continuous
	MEX-Phobos astrometric dataset to date---offers substantially improved
	leverage for constraining Phobos' tidal dissipation parameters and 
	secular orbital evolution. Residuals with respect to JPL MAR099 show 
	standard deviations of 0.468 km in $\alpha\cos\delta$ and 0.501 km in 
	$\delta$, with near-zero mean offsets of 0.009 km and 0.033 km, 
	respectively, indicating good overall agreement while revealing residual 
	systematics that may inform future ephemeris refinements. This dataset 
	serves as a critical astrometric reference for the upcoming JAXA MMX 
	mission (2029).

Description:
    The data is given in the form of table, This table contains 732 
    astrometric positions of Phobos derived from Mars Express Super 
    Resolution Channel (SRC) images spanning 2007-2025. Positions are 
    given as spacecraft-centered right ascension, declination, and 
    Phobos position vector in the International Celestial Reference 
    Frame (ICRF).

